  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/779601951?book_show_action=true">Dec 03, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Diann Blakely" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Diann Blakely" href="/user/show/4686484-diann-blakely">Diann Blakely</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer779601951" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16722340551591107292">To read Hélène Cardona’s poems in this book is to dream the body back to a time when it still flew feathered through air, still breathed through gills, then first slumped its heft to feel sand prick its tender and virginal flesh. The French poems printed en face serve to enhance the blurring of borders in a way that is purely Cardona--as personal as a dream--but now shared.</span>

          </span>
        </div>


